AGI - The climate catastrophe that struck Brazil, causing more than one hundred deaths and almost two million displaced, has generated a series of bizarre conspiring theories, some of which concern the infamous "chemical sciences" or alleged " Weather antennas" installed in the distant Alaska.&nbsp; As often happens in the face of this kind of disasters, and of the great uncertainty behind them, these theories take space and become viral on social media.&nbsp; "What is happening in the Rio Grande do Sul is not absolutely natural," reads by more users, in various versions, on X. "Let's open our eyes!" One of the guilty, among those who believe in premeditated events, is indicated in the HAARP (High-frequency Active Auroral Research Program)>, an American project that studies the ionosphere using huge antennas placed in Alaska.&nbsp; Other users posted images of planes that cross the skies of the Brazilian state of Rio Grande do Sul, the territory most affected by heavy rains, stating that jet-leaded condensed skies contain toxic chemicals that are part of a secret government program. Taken together, theories paint a disturbing picture that somehow denies climate change, at the same time blaming governments and scientific institutions that would be orchestrating "planned tragedy" for dark reasons. These theories ignore the overwhelming scientific consensus that climate change is almost certainly the basis of a global increase in extreme weather events.&nbsp;
<h2> What scientists say
Carlos Nobre, who heads the National Institute of Science and Technology for Climate Change (INCT) of Brazil, has listed what scientists believe is the basis of the disastrous rains of recent times: a low-pressure system was blocked by a high-pressure system in the middle-west and south-east of the country.&nbsp; Global warming has aggravated the situation, said Nobre: "The warmest atmosphere can store much more water vapour, feeding more frequent and intense rainy episodes leading to disasters like this." The Brazilian government agrees: President Luiz Inacio Lula da Silva declared the tragedy an "alarm" for the planet. On the contrary, its predecessor - the extreme right-wing president Jair Bolsonaro - has weakened the application of environmental norms and minimized the impact of climate change. A recent Quaest survey, however, found that almost all Brazilians believe that climate change is, at least in part, responsible for the disaster in Rio Grande do Sul.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
<div </div
<br> However, conspiracist theories that once could be dismissed as unimportant, have acquired new life&nbsp; thanks to these events in the southern regions.&nbsp; All though, for example, the process behind jets' "chemical jets" has long been known: jet engines leave visible jets of condensed water vapor, as well as small amounts of soots and pollutants. Nothing strange, mysterious or arcane.&nbsp; The HAARP project, originally funded partly by the U.S. Army, is now run by the University of Alaska, in Fairbanks, where scientists use antennas for high-power radio transmissions to study the ionosphere, without obviously manipulating atmospheric time.&nbsp;
Nobre, like many other scientists, argues that HAARP theories "have absolutely no meaning. There is no way, for a tool in the ionosphere, to make weather events more extreme," he said.
&nbsp;
Raquel Recuero,&nbsp; one of the leaders of social communications at the Federal University of Pelotas, in Rio Grande do Sul, said that conspiracy theories were probably spread by organized groups "in search of public, monetization and influence". Such theories find fertile ground when people are desperately looking for explanations - however unlikely - for some deeply worrying phenomenon. The ideas stick, he added, when they merge with important issues for people, like "political and religious speeches". But he added that, although they tend to strengthen conservative and extremist beliefs, they cannot be linked to a single political movement.
Recuero said that people's trust in the fundamental pillars of democracy is undermined by these attacks on government authorities, scientists and the press, all accused of manipulating the truth.&nbsp; The challenge, he said, is to raise public awareness about what is happening and to help people understand "what is true and what is false".
